{"entity": "Citrus", "type": "naturalobject", "description": "Citrus is a genus of plants belonging to the Rutaceae family, known for its preference for warm and humid climates. It is one of the ten major fruit types covered in pest and disease management manuals, reflecting its significance in agricultural systems. In China, Citrus is the fruit crop with the largest cultivation area and highest output, underscoring its economic and agronomic importance. As a host plant, Citrus is vulnerable to nearly 100 diseases and 354 insect pests, making it a primary target for integrated pest and disease management strategies. Among these threats, scale insects cause damage to leaves, twigs, and fruits, while the Peach Fruit Borer larvae also rely on Citrus as a host. Specific diseases such as citrus scab are effectively managed using fungicides like 46% copper hydroxide and 20% thiodiazole-copper, with strict application timing and safety intervals required to ensure both efficacy and consumer safety. The crop is subject to regulated pesticide use, including defined safety intervals and application limits, emphasizing the need for careful adherence to treatment schedules. These characteristics collectively position Citrus as a central focus in fruit crop protection programs worldwide."}
{"entity": "Citrus Resin Disease", "type": "concept", "description": "Citrus Resin Disease is another name for the same disease caused by Diaporthe citri, with symptoms varying by infection site such as gummosis on branches or stem-end rot in storage.<SEP>A citrus disease causing symptoms on branches, trunks, and fruits, potentially leading to tree death; also known as gummosis.<SEP>A fungal disease affecting citrus trees, controlled by the 80% captan product."}
{"entity": "Sooty Mold Disease", "type": "concept", "description": "Sooty mold disease, also known as coal smoke disease or coal disease, affects citrus plants by forming black霉layers on leaves, shoots, and fruits, impairing photosynthesis.<SEP>Sooty mold disease is a fungal condition that develops on honeydew secreted by Citrus Whitefly, covering leaves with a black霉layer that blocks sunlight and impairs photosynthesis, particularly severe in August and September.<SEP>Sooty mold disease is a fungal condition triggered by the sticky honeydew secreted by the Grape Two-Spotted Leafhopper, which contaminates leaves and fruit clusters.<SEP>A fungal disease triggered by honeydew secretions from Aleuroplatus pectiniferus infestations, impairing photosynthesis and weakening trees."}
{"entity": "Thiophanate-Methyl", "type": "method", "description": "Thiophanate-methyl is a wettable powder fungicide applied at 300× dilution for treating infected bark areas.<SEP>Thiophanate-Methyl (70% wettable powder) is applied at 150x dilution to high-risk areas of the tree for disease control.<SEP>Thiophanate-Methyl is a systemic fungicide used at 70% concentration diluted 800–1000 times to treat Loquat Leaf Spot."}
{"entity": "Citrus Tree", "type": "naturalobject", "description": "Citrus Tree is a fruit-bearing tree that serves as the host plant for a range of pests and pathogens, including Citrus Scab, Resin Disease, Citrus Whitefly, Unaspis yanonensis, citrus red mite, scale insects, citrus psyllid, and citrus red spider mites. These pests cause damage to multiple parts of the tree, affecting leaves, shoots, fruits, and branches. The tree is also the primary target crop for various pesticide applications aimed at managing these infestations and diseases. Pesticide treatments include abamectin, applied to control rust mites with a pre-harvest interval of 21 days and limited to two applications per crop cycle, and 20% Dingfumite Suspension Concentrate, used for mite control across all growth stages. Additionally, fungicides are applied before or at the onset of disease, with up to three applications permitted per season and a mandatory 21-day pre-harvest interval to ensure safety. These management practices are essential for maintaining tree health and ensuring safe, high-quality fruit production. The consistent application protocols reflect the need for careful timing and adherence to usage limits to prevent resistance and environmental impact while supporting sustainable citrus cultivation."}
{"entity": "21% Copper Abietate Aqueous Emulsion", "type": "product", "description": "A copper-based fungicidal emulsion containing 21% copper abietate, applied at 600–750-fold dilution for disease prevention."}
{"entity": "Citrus Scab", "type": "concept", "description": "Citrus scab is a major fungal disease affecting young tissues such as spring shoots, tender leaves, young fruits, and flower buds.<SEP>Citrus Scab is a fungal disease affecting citrus plants, also known as sandpaper disease or black spot depending on the affected plant part.<SEP>A citrus disease also known as Citrus Blast or Gummosis, caused by Colletotrichum gloeosporioides and characterized by bark cracking and gum exudation.<SEP>A disease affecting citrus trees, preventable and treatable with dithianon-based formulations.<SEP>A fungal disease of citrus crops, targeted by 250g/L pyraclostrobin suspension concentrate.<SEP>A fungal disease in citrus crops that can be controlled using 46% copper hydroxide water-dispersible granules.<SEP>A fungal disease affecting citrus, managed using 80% sulfur water-dispersible granules starting at spring shoot emergence, avoiding application during flowering."}
{"entity": "Chaetothyrium Spinigerum", "type": "creature", "description": "A fungal species in the genus Chaetothyrium (Ascomycotina) implicated in citrus sooty blotch.<SEP>Chaetothyrium spinigerum is a fungal species in the Ascomycotina subphylum and Chaetothyrium genus, causing sooty mold on citrus."}
{"entity": "Citrus Diseases", "type": "concept", "description": "Major citrus diseases in East China include scab, gummosis, anthracnose, powdery mildew, sooty blotch, blue mold, green mold, and damping-off in seedlings."}
{"entity": "Diaporthe Citri", "type": "creature", "description": "Diaporthe citri (Fawcett) Wolf is the causal fungus of Citrus Scab, belonging to the Ascomycota phylum and Elsinoe genus."}
{"entity": "周吉生", "type": "person", "description": "周吉生is an author of a study on apple anthracnose and its control techniques."}
{"entity": "苹果炭疽病", "type": "concept", "description": "苹果炭疽病is a fungal disease affecting apple trees, studied for its control techniques."}
```

